            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "I don't think it's possible to recieve the server's IP address through the WSGI interface (the equivalent to servlet in Java, i think). If you find another Python WSGI framework which is able to do that, then it certainly would be possible in Flask. Some alternative data that might be equally useful for logging:\n- `flask.request.host`, which is basically the host header.\n- Some custom environment variable, WSGI environment variable or header, which you can set through the application server you use. [headers](http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.10/api/#flask.Request.headers) are readable through `flask.request.headers`\n- Any of `path`, `script_root`, `url`, `base_url`, `url_root` on the `flask.request` object, see http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.10/api/#flask.Request.path\n"
        },
